article.description: Janell Burse scored 18 points and Lauren Jackson added 15 as the visiting Seattle Storm handed the Detroit Shock their first loss of the season 76-61 Wednesday night.
article.headline: Seattle breaks it open early with 22-4 run
article.linkText: Visiting Storm hand Shock first loss of the season
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock had come to believe
they could overcome any deficit and still win.

The Seattle Storm proved them wrong.

Janell Burse scored 18 points and Lauren Jackson added 15 as the
Storm jumped out to a big lead and handed the Shock their first
loss of the season, 76-61 Wednesday night.

Detroit won its last two games with frantic last-minute rallies,
but never got closer than 10 in the second half against Seattle.

"We've seen what they can do," Seattle coach Anne Donovan
said. "We knew we didn't want to let them get in a position to do
that to us."

The Shock (4-1) were the only undefeated team left in the
league.

"We've been walking around thinking that we are hot stuff
because we were 4-0," Cheryl Ford said. "We found out today that
we aren't a good team. We might be OK."

Seattle (5-2) won for the fifth time in six games, despite
missing Sue Bird, who was not with the team after breaking two
bones in her face in a collision with Jackson during Tuesday
night's loss in Connecticut.

"We all wanted to play well for Sue," Jackson said.
"Especially me, since I'm the one that did it."

Bird's college and Olympic teammate, Swin Cash of Detroit, has
missed the entire season recovering from a knee injury.

Betty Lennox added 13 points for Seattle.

"I think we might have surprised Detroit," Lennox said. "I
think people still think our championship last year was a fluke."

Deanna Nolan scored 23 for the Shock and rookie Kara Braxton had
15.

"I'm not even sure you can contain Nolan at this point,"
Donovan said. "You just do the best you can and try to keep your
focus on everyone else."

Seattle broke the game open early, going on a 22-4 first-half
run to take a 32-10 lead. Jackson, Burse and Lennox scored the
Storm's first 32 points.

"The effort is not there when we come out," Shock coach Bill
Laimbeer said. "It's not pretty to watch."

The Storm led 43-22 at the half, but Lennox limped off the court
in the first minute of the second period and Detroit started a
rally.

The Shock soon made it 46-36 and were looking for a third
straight comeback victory, but Lennox's return helped Seattle
regain control with a 9-2 run.
